{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"2058fce9-10d3-478b-92cb-efb404071b86","content":"The migration is straightforward. In your project file, either **remove** the `<UseVSTest>true</UseVSTest>` property or set it to `false`:\n\n```xml\n<Project Sdk=\"MSTest.Sdk/3.8.0\">\n  <PropertyGroup>\n    <!-- Remove or set to false: -->\n    <!-- <UseVSTest>true</UseVSTest> -->\n  </PropertyGroup>\n</Project>\n```\n\n**Key changes / things to know:**\n\n1. **Remove `<UseVSTest>true</UseVSTest>`** — MSTest.Sdk defaults to Microsoft.Testing.Platform when this property is absent or `false`.\n2. **CLI change** — Run tests with `dotnet test` as before, but you can also use `dotnet run` on the test project directly (it's now an executable).\n3. **Remove legacy packages** — If you explicitly reference `Microsoft.NET.Test.Sdk`, `MSTest.TestAdapter`, or `MSTest.TestFramework`, remove them; the SDK handles everything.\n4. **Check tool compatibility** — Some VS Test-specific `.runsettings` options or third-party adapters may need updates. Microsoft.Testing.Platform uses its own extensibility model.\n5. **CI pipelines** — If your CI uses `dotnet test --logger trx`, that still works, but verify any custom loggers or filters.\n\nThat's it — the MSTest SDK does the heavy lifting. Remove the one property and rebuild.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"f2feb699-7757-4dfe-9757-e0aee41b1d72","outputTokens":346,"requestId":"703E:1B693D:DA74DF1:F0B9AE4:69F2A844"},"id":"3c24d997-91cf-432f-b83a-44747d08bee0","timestamp":"2026-04-30T00:54:39.617Z","parentId":"651ca94e-4cb3-4e0e-9583-df73964188e6"}
